JEREMY SALIBA: There's been a
few aspects of the project.

00:44:52.540 --> 00:44:55.270
Volume Two is almost, in
a sense, doing that.

00:44:55.270 --> 00:44:58.490
So we've had that chance, in
a way, to kind of-- we're

00:44:58.490 --> 00:45:00.770
locking down things and being
a little more stringent on

00:45:00.770 --> 00:45:04.465
what the students contribute
to the book.

00:45:04.465 --> 00:45:07.900
Being more selective about
who's on the book.

00:45:07.900 --> 00:45:11.230
BRIAN SCHIRMER: Again, at this
point, we've done it.

00:45:11.230 --> 00:45:14.920
We've done the entire pipeline
once, and the entire thing was

00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:15.590
a learning experience.

00:45:15.590 --> 00:45:17.070
I'd never run a Kickstarter.

00:45:17.070 --> 00:45:21.420
I'd never submitted anything
to Amazon.

00:45:21.420 --> 00:45:24.500
And meeting industry folks and
basically going up to them

00:45:24.500 --> 00:45:26.520
cold and saying,
hey, I'm Brian.

00:45:26.520 --> 00:45:28.920
This is my book, blah.

00:45:28.920 --> 00:45:33.780
Now that all of that is done,
there were bumps in all those

00:45:33.780 --> 00:45:36.720
aspects along the way,
and now we've

00:45:36.720 --> 00:45:39.750
corrected for that, I think.

00:45:39.750 --> 00:45:43.110
But as far as changing anything
from the outset--

00:45:43.110 --> 00:45:44.970
like would we have changed
any aspect of the story?

00:45:44.970 --> 00:45:47.300
Would we have done the class

00:45:47.300 --> 00:45:49.320
differently from the beginning?

00:45:49.320 --> 00:45:50.416
I don't think so.

00:45:50.416 --> 00:45:51.130
JEREMY SALIBA: No.

00:45:51.130 --> 00:45:52.100
It worked out.

00:45:52.100 --> 00:45:52.670
It was great.

00:45:52.670 --> 00:45:53.150
It was a of fun.

00:45:53.150 --> 00:45:53.980
It worked really well.

00:45:53.980 --> 00:45:55.150
That's probably why we
went back for more.

00:45:55.150 --> 00:45:57.310
BRIAN SCHIRMER: And I want to
say that I was very blessed

00:45:57.310 --> 00:46:00.280
with the fact that Jeremy agreed
to be a part of this

00:46:00.280 --> 00:46:03.450
and to actually teach
the class.

00:46:07.520 --> 00:46:10.610
I can talk about three point
perspective, and I can talk

00:46:10.610 --> 00:46:16.240
about crossing the line, but
I can't-- the minutia of

00:46:16.240 --> 00:46:19.310
artistic critiques
is way beyond me.

00:46:19.310 --> 00:46:20.470
JEREMY SALIBA: It was a lot of
fun because I get to tell

00:46:20.470 --> 00:46:22.070
people how much I hate
their artwork and how

00:46:22.070 --> 00:46:25.110
it should be better.

00:46:25.110 --> 00:46:26.770
As long as you learn
a few terms--

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:29.030
well, you should select this
out and make sure that the

00:46:29.030 --> 00:46:30.250
line of sight's good here--

00:46:30.250 --> 00:46:32.010
you sound like you know what
you're talking about.

00:46:32.010 --> 00:46:32.890
Yeah?

00:46:32.890 --> 00:46:34.300
AUDIENCE: I was curious
[INAUDIBLE]

00:46:40.285 --> 00:46:42.900
who did what and what kind of
feedback did you give people,

00:46:42.900 --> 00:46:45.810
get this to change.

00:46:45.810 --> 00:46:46.950
JEREMY SALIBA: Thank you.

00:46:46.950 --> 00:46:49.360
What kind of process, what kind
of feedback did we do

00:46:49.360 --> 00:46:50.730
through the progression
of everything?

00:46:50.730 --> 00:46:53.400
This is one of our returning
artists, Mr. John Gomes.

00:46:53.400 --> 00:46:57.000
And this is another situation
where we had the good fortune

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:00.720
to know his strengths and
weaknesses, if any.

00:47:00.720 --> 00:47:03.960
And so we knew this was going
to be a big splash page.

00:47:03.960 --> 00:47:08.980
So initially, he hadn't done
anything like city street

00:47:08.980 --> 00:47:10.620
scenes before this.

00:47:10.620 --> 00:47:12.230
So I just pulled him aside and
said, hey, you better get the

00:47:12.230 --> 00:47:13.900
perspective perfect on this.

00:47:13.900 --> 00:47:14.850
It's got to be good.

00:47:14.850 --> 00:47:16.220
You know, get reference.

00:47:16.220 --> 00:47:17.400
I'm going to ride you like--

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:19.680
BRIAN SCHIRMER: I want to jump
in real quick and say when we

00:47:19.680 --> 00:47:22.890
wrote this in the script, I not
only envisioned that it

00:47:22.890 --> 00:47:26.990
was going to be in Paris, but
also, when I thought of it, I

00:47:26.990 --> 00:47:30.500
pictured the cover of
"Freewheelin' Bob Dylan." And

00:47:30.500 --> 00:47:32.570
I basically took an image--

00:47:32.570 --> 00:47:34.640
which is another thing that I
actually do in the script is I

00:47:34.640 --> 00:47:37.300
will find imagery and reference
online, throw it in

00:47:37.300 --> 00:47:38.080
the script.

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:40.680
So I had the album cover there,
and he riffed on that

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:41.140
beautifully.

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:43.540
But please, continue.

00:47:43.540 --> 00:47:44.840
JEREMY SALIBA: So let me see.

00:47:44.840 --> 00:47:47.280
Well, you can kind of see
some of the progression.

00:47:47.280 --> 00:47:49.350
Like, obviously, it's a loose
sketch in the beginning

00:47:49.350 --> 00:47:52.310
anyways, so it's
very malleable.

00:47:52.310 --> 00:47:53.900
We can talk about things.

00:47:53.900 --> 00:47:55.660
And I thought the placement of
some of the cars could use a

00:47:55.660 --> 00:47:58.290
little bit of massaging, the
one on the left especially.

00:47:58.290 --> 00:48:00.800
And I thought that
the buildings--

00:48:00.800 --> 00:48:02.500
there wasn't enough of a
cavernous kind of a feel.

00:48:02.500 --> 00:48:04.600
I wanted it to be a little bit
taller, have a little bit more

00:48:04.600 --> 00:48:06.130
of a corridor that
they were in.

00:48:06.130 --> 00:48:07.930
So those were kind of
my instructions.

00:48:07.930 --> 00:48:09.160
I also thought the street
looked-- because this was

00:48:09.160 --> 00:48:10.960
supposed to be-- what was
the year that this

00:48:10.960 --> 00:48:12.300
scene takes place in?

00:48:12.300 --> 00:48:14.540
BRIAN SCHIRMER: Our alternate
1930, I believe.

00:48:14.540 --> 00:48:14.910
JEREMY SALIBA: Right.

00:48:14.910 --> 00:48:16.700
And the street looked a little
too modern paved in the

00:48:16.700 --> 00:48:18.540
initial sketch, so I was like,
maybe even go with, like,

00:48:18.540 --> 00:48:21.700
cobblestone or something
like that.

00:48:21.700 --> 00:48:24.890
At which point, he made
those corrections.

00:48:24.890 --> 00:48:29.630
On this stage, there's some
subtle small things.

00:48:29.630 --> 00:48:30.410
He was doing great.

00:48:30.410 --> 00:48:32.460
This one is just a
great example.

00:48:32.460 --> 00:48:36.476
But the folds in Frankenstein's
sleeves were

00:48:36.476 --> 00:48:37.830
just a little unnatural
in the beginning.

00:48:37.830 --> 00:48:40.500
We had to kind of
get reference.

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:43.110
It's one of those things where
we'll discuss it and say,

00:48:43.110 --> 00:48:44.830
well, if you're not sure,
get reference.

00:48:44.830 --> 00:48:46.830
And if you can't find the
reference, let me know because

00:48:46.830 --> 00:48:50.940
I'll find you the reference, and
push forward from there.

00:48:50.940 --> 00:48:53.476
From that point on, after we
refined the sketch and got to

00:48:53.476 --> 00:48:55.080
where we wanted it to
be, it was the inks.

00:48:55.080 --> 00:48:58.290
And I didn't have to do much
with him on the inks.

00:48:58.290 --> 00:48:59.860
He knows his inking well.

00:48:59.860 --> 00:49:02.940
And I liked what he handled with
the silhouettes and how

00:49:02.940 --> 00:49:05.780
he hit at a higher-contrast
area right here with black

00:49:05.780 --> 00:49:08.780
behind the characters that were
primarily bright to make

00:49:08.780 --> 00:49:10.120
that a focal point.

00:49:10.120 --> 00:49:12.490
And again, with the readjusting
of these diagonal

00:49:12.490 --> 00:49:15.120
lines of perspective to lead
us right to where we wanted

00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:19.070
the eye to go, it was just a
matter of letting him have his

00:49:19.070 --> 00:49:21.550
fun with it and go crazy.

00:49:21.550 --> 00:49:25.460
Then with the color image,
again, he did a great job.

00:49:25.460 --> 00:49:26.520
We had the reference.

00:49:26.520 --> 00:49:28.560
We kind of established a palette
for everything at this

00:49:28.560 --> 00:49:30.460
point already.

00:49:30.460 --> 00:49:34.780
I don't know if I ever had a
specific conversation about

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:37.510
the red dress with him,
the color of it.

00:49:37.510 --> 00:49:38.960
But it's a great choice.

00:49:38.960 --> 00:49:42.190
It complements the green nicely
and, again, reinforces

00:49:42.190 --> 00:49:44.510
that focal point.

00:49:44.510 --> 00:49:47.130
So that's kind of a typical walk
through of the kind of

00:49:47.130 --> 00:49:48.940
things that we would talk
about to make it

00:49:48.940 --> 00:49:50.230
as good as we can.

00:49:50.230 --> 00:49:52.830
BRIAN SCHIRMER: Well, sure.

00:49:52.830 --> 00:49:53.730
JEREMY SALIBA: Yes, sir?

00:49:53.730 --> 00:49:56.670
AUDIENCE: How do you figure out
who worked on which panels

00:49:56.670 --> 00:49:59.610
and do you ever have multiple
students working on the same

00:49:59.610 --> 00:50:01.570
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:01.570 --> 00:50:02.340
JEREMY SALIBA: Yes.

00:50:02.340 --> 00:50:04.410
BRIAN SCHIRMER: How
did [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:04.410 --> 00:50:05.260
Yeah.

00:50:05.260 --> 00:50:07.195
How did we determine who worked
on which pages, and did

00:50:07.195 --> 00:50:13.470
we have people collaborating
on any specific pages?

00:50:13.470 --> 00:50:17.220
Basically two questions,
we have two answers.

00:50:17.220 --> 00:50:19.450
Like I said, this was a
portfolio-driven class.

00:50:19.450 --> 00:50:21.470
We had to see what the students
were capable of

00:50:21.470 --> 00:50:23.890
before we admitted them
to the class.

00:50:23.890 --> 00:50:25.040
So we were able look at that.

00:50:25.040 --> 00:50:27.220
And then, usually, in the first
week or two, they are

00:50:27.220 --> 00:50:31.200
doing concept designs for,
perhaps, new elements.

00:50:31.200 --> 00:50:33.690
And Jeremy and I will,
basically, we will have read

00:50:33.690 --> 00:50:34.100
the script.

00:50:34.100 --> 00:50:39.340
We will sit down, knowing each
person's strengths, and we'll

00:50:39.340 --> 00:50:41.920
say, well, this person might be
best suited for these pages

00:50:41.920 --> 00:50:45.420
or this character and so on.

00:50:45.420 --> 00:50:48.390
And I don't think we've ever
had anyone complain.

00:50:48.390 --> 00:50:48.920
JEREMY SALIBA: Right.

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:50.110
BRIAN SCHIRMER: We do
occasionally get requests

00:50:50.110 --> 00:50:53.000
saying, oh, I definitely
want to do Dracula.

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:55.580
And where we can accommodate,
we do.

00:50:55.580 --> 00:50:56.160
JEREMY SALIBA: Right, right.

00:50:56.160 --> 00:50:57.460
We want them to have fun.

00:50:57.460 --> 00:50:58.560
And then in collaboration--

00:50:58.560 --> 00:51:02.050
the main collaboration I can
think of in Volume One, two of

00:51:02.050 --> 00:51:03.270
our students worked
on the same page.

00:51:03.270 --> 00:51:05.140
One of them penciled it, and one
of them inked it, which is

00:51:05.140 --> 00:51:06.930
a common way to work in the
comics field anyways.

00:51:06.930 --> 00:51:07.940
And they did a great job.

00:51:07.940 --> 00:51:08.720
It was the kiss.

00:51:08.720 --> 00:51:12.480
BRIAN SCHIRMER: But more often
than not, again, because it's

00:51:12.480 --> 00:51:15.690
a class and students need to be
learning all the different

00:51:15.690 --> 00:51:18.690
aspects, you've got a student
doing everything.

00:51:18.690 --> 00:51:20.710
Like in this case, John did
the original pencils.

00:51:20.710 --> 00:51:21.850
He did the final pencils.

00:51:21.850 --> 00:51:24.870
He did the inks, and
he did the colors.

00:51:24.870 --> 00:51:25.910
JEREMY SALIBA: The other thing
that Brian does, he caters

00:51:25.910 --> 00:51:28.090
specifically to the needs of
the students in the class.

00:51:28.090 --> 00:51:30.570
In Book Two, he made sure
to have everyone have a

00:51:30.570 --> 00:51:32.120
consistent chunk and a run.

00:51:32.120 --> 00:51:34.190
So when they have their
portfolio to present to

00:51:34.190 --> 00:51:36.586
someone, they've got a nice,
clean run of the story so they

00:51:36.586 --> 00:51:37.230
can show it to someone.

00:51:37.230 --> 00:51:38.700
BRIAN SCHIRMER: Right.

00:51:38.700 --> 00:51:44.300
We have learned from contacts
in the industry that when

00:51:44.300 --> 00:51:47.670
recruiters are looking at work
that students, or anyone, has

00:51:47.670 --> 00:51:51.520
done, who is basically looking
for a job as a sequential

00:51:51.520 --> 00:51:54.110
artist, they want to see pages
of sequential storytelling.

00:51:54.110 --> 00:51:58.290
They don't want cover design,
cover design, cover design or

00:51:58.290 --> 00:51:59.630
just random pages
here and there.

00:51:59.630 --> 00:52:01.000
They want to see that
you can tell a good

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:02.490
story straight through.

00:52:02.490 --> 00:52:04.180
JEREMY SALIBA: Right.

00:52:04.180 --> 00:52:05.026
BRIAN SCHIRMER: Sir?

00:52:05.026 --> 00:52:07.010
AUDIENCE: So the Kickstarter
portion.

00:52:07.010 --> 00:52:10.978
There was a lot of stuff that
seemed time consuming to you

00:52:10.978 --> 00:52:12.962
guys-- the Kickstarter
[INAUDIBLE]

00:52:12.962 --> 00:52:13.458
Amazon.

00:52:13.458 --> 00:52:15.442
So I assume that will get
easier this time.

00:52:15.442 --> 00:52:16.434
Maybe not.

00:52:16.434 --> 00:52:20.402
But you envision a future
with that, where that

00:52:20.402 --> 00:52:22.386
part isn't as necessary?

00:52:22.386 --> 00:52:23.636
Or [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:26.540 --> 00:52:27.870
self-reinforcing?

00:52:27.870 --> 00:52:30.290
BRIAN SCHIRMER: Do we envision
a future where we don't need

00:52:30.290 --> 00:52:30.630
Kickstarter?

00:52:30.630 --> 00:52:34.180
Would that be a good
way [INAUDIBLE]?

00:52:34.180 --> 00:52:37.850
Short answer, at
this stage, no.

00:52:37.850 --> 00:52:42.830
Only because, as Jeremy said,
it's more than a passion

00:52:42.830 --> 00:52:45.660
project, but it is not
uber lucrative.

00:52:45.660 --> 00:52:46.100
Let's put it that way.

00:52:46.100 --> 00:52:47.310
The money that does
come through

00:52:47.310 --> 00:52:48.925
does pay for the printing.

00:52:48.925 --> 00:52:50.900
It does pay for the shipping.

00:52:50.900 --> 00:52:54.490
It does pay for some of the
rewards or the perks

00:52:54.490 --> 00:52:56.290
and what have you.

00:52:56.290 --> 00:53:00.250
But we're not sitting on a big
bag with a dollar sign on it

00:53:00.250 --> 00:53:03.982
that then allows us
to go forward.

00:53:03.982 --> 00:53:05.000
MALE SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE]
time.

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:06.212
BRIAN SCHIRMER: OK.

00:53:06.212 --> 00:53:06.590
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:53:06.590 --> 00:53:06.910
BRIAN SCHIRMER: Thank you.

00:53:06.910 --> 00:53:07.670
Thank you very much.

00:53:07.670 --> 00:53:07.870
JEREMY SALIBA: Yeah,
thanks everyonne.

00:53:07.870 --> 00:53:08.670
BRIAN SCHIRMER: Thank
you, Google.

00:53:08.670 --> 00:53:09.920
Yay.

